<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900731-0121</DOCNO><DOCID>900731-0121.</DOCID><HL>   Otis, Soviet Agency   Form Joint Venture   For Elevator Market</HL><DATE>07/31/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   FREST UTX</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   FARMINGTON, Conn. -- Otis Elevator Co. said it is forminga joint venture in the Soviet Union to pursue the $1billion-a-year market for new elevators.   Otis, a wholly owned subsidiary of United TechnologiesCorp., said it will own 55% of a new company that willmanufacture, install and service elevators in the SovietUnion using Otis designs, manufacturing technology, andinstallation and maintenance methods. The rest of thepartnership will be formed by Shcherbinka Lift Plant, a unitof Liftmash, the Soviet agency responsible for makingelevators.</LP><TEXT>   Otis said it also will supply manufacturing equipment,management personnel and training for Soviet workers at a newfacility under construction at the existing Shcherbinka LiftPlant, 15 miles from Moscow. The plant will make elevatorequipment for offices and small hotels, Otis said.   The Soviet Union is the world's largest national marketfor new elevator equipment, with demand for 60,000 new unitsa year, Otis said.   Otis is the world's largest elevator company, with 1989revenue of $3.3 billion, 70% of which came from outside ofthe U.S.   United Technologies, based in Hartford, Conn., also hasinterests in aerospace, air conditioning and automotiveproducts.</TEXT></DOC>